VALUES
(41, 4, 5, 42, 8, 6, 6, 'where it had not much earth', 'Connection of Seed on Stony Ground', 'Both passages emphasize the seed that falls on unyielding surfaces, leading to its quick growth but eventual demise. The lack of depth in Mark parallels the lack of moisture in Luke, highlighting the challenges faced by the seed.', 'parallel', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 5, 26, 11, 19, 19, 'stony ground', 'Connection of Stony Hearts', 'This connection highlights the theme of ''stony'' conditions in both passages. Mark describes seeds falling on ''stony ground,'' while Ezekiel speaks of removing a ''stony heart'' to give a new spirit.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 5, 28, 10, 12, 12, NULL, 'Ground and Growth Connection', 'This connection highlights the imagery of ground in both passages. Mark 4:5 mentions ''stony ground'' which contrasts with Hosea 10:12''s call to ''break up your fallow ground,'' emphasizing the need for depth and preparation for growth.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 5, 30, 6, 12, 12, 'stony ground', 'Connection of Stony Ground and Judgment', 'This connection highlights the theme of unfruitfulness in challenging conditions. Both passages emphasize the lack of depth and the futility of efforts in unsuitable environments.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 5, 42, 8, 13, 13, 'no depth of earth', 'Connection of Stony Ground', 'Both passages emphasize the lack of depth in the soil, illustrating how the word is received with joy but fails to take root. This connection highlights the theme of temporary belief that does not endure through challenges.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 5, 40, 13, 5, 6, 'stony ground', 'Connection of Stony Ground', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''stony ground'' where the seed lacks depth. They describe how the seed springs up quickly but ultimately withers due to insufficient roots. This connection highlights the shared imagery and theme of growth hindered by poor soil conditions.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 6, 24, 17, 5, 8, 'no root', 'Connection of Root and Trust', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of having deep roots for stability and growth. In Mark, the plant withers due to lack of root, while Jeremiah contrasts the cursed man with the blessed man who is like a tree planted by water, highlighting the necessity of trust in the Lord.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 6, 32, 4, 8, 8, 'the sun was up', 'Connection of Scorching Sun', 'Both passages emphasize the impact of the sun''s heat. In Mark, the sun causes the plant to wither due to lack of root, while in Jonah, the sun''s heat leads Jonah to faint and wish for death.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 6, 59, 1, 11, 11, 'withered away', 'Connection of Withering and Riches', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of withering due to harsh conditions. In Mark, the plant withers from the sun''s heat, while James illustrates how the rich man fades away similarly under pressure. This connection highlights the transient nature of both life and wealth.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 6, 19, 1, 3, 4, 'it had no root', 'Contrast of Growth and Withering', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of roots and stability for growth. Mark 4:6 describes a plant that withers due to lack of root, while Psalms 1:3 highlights a tree that thrives and does not wither when planted by water.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 6, 19, 92, 13, 15, 'no root', 'Flourishing and Rootedness', 'This connection highlights the importance of being rooted in God for flourishing. While Mark 4:6 describes a plant that withers due to lack of root, Psalms 92:13-15 emphasizes that those planted in the house of the Lord will flourish.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 6, 23, 25, 4, 4, NULL, 'Heat and Protection Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the effects of heat and the need for protection. Mark 4:6 describes the scorching heat that causes withering, while Isaiah 25:4 speaks of refuge from heat, highlighting the contrast between vulnerability and divine shelter.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 6, 49, 3, 17, 17, 'root', 'Rootedness in Faith and Love', 'This connection highlights the importance of being ''rooted'' in faith and love. The SOURCE verse illustrates the consequences of lacking roots, while the TARGET passage emphasizes being ''rooted and grounded'' in love, suggesting a thematic link between spiritual stability and growth.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 7, 24, 4, 3, 3, 'among thorns', 'Connection of Thorns in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the detrimental effect of thorns on growth. Mark describes how thorns choke the seed, while Jeremiah warns against sowing among thorns, indicating a similar theme of hindrance to fruitful outcomes.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 7, 42, 8, 14, 14, 'choked it, and it yielded no fruit', 'Connection of Thorns and Fruitlessness', 'Both passages emphasize the idea of being choked by thorns, which leads to a lack of fruit. The source verse mentions thorns choking the seed, while the target passage elaborates on the cares and pleasures of life causing the same outcome.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 7, 1, 3, 17, 18, 'thorns', 'Thorns and Their Consequences', 'Both passages emphasize the role of thorns as symbols of struggle and unfruitfulness. In Mark, thorns choke the seed, preventing it from yielding fruit, while in Genesis, thorns are a consequence of the curse on the ground, representing the toil of life.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 7, 62, 2, 15, 16, 'yielded no fruit', 'Connection of Worldly Distractions', 'Both passages emphasize the dangers of distractions that prevent spiritual growth. In Mark, thorns choke the seed, while in 1 John, love for the world leads to spiritual emptiness.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 7, 40, 13, 7, 7, 'fell among thorns', 'Connection of Thorns in Parables', 'Both passages emphasize the imagery of thorns choking the seeds, illustrating a similar message about obstacles to growth. The parallel phrasing indicates a shared teaching on the challenges faced by the word.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 7, 40, 13, 22, 22, 'among thorns', 'Connection of Thorns and Unfruitfulness', 'Both passages emphasize the impact of thorns on seed growth, illustrating how external distractions can hinder spiritual productivity. The thorns in both verses symbolize worldly concerns that prevent the word from bearing fruit.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 7, 41, 4, 18, 19, 'thorns grew up, and choked it', 'Connection of Thorns and Unfruitfulness', 'Both passages emphasize the impact of thorns on growth. The source verse describes thorns choking the seed, while the target passage explains how worldly cares and desires similarly choke the word, leading to unfruitfulness.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 8, 43, 15, 5, 5, NULL, 'Fruitfulness in Christ', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of yielding fruit. Mark highlights the increase of fruit from good ground, while John states that abiding in Christ leads to bringing forth much fruit.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 8, 51, 1, 6, 6, NULL, 'Fruitfulness in the Gospel', 'This connection highlights the theme of fruitfulness in both passages. Mark speaks of good ground yielding fruit, while Colossians emphasizes the Gospel bringing forth fruit in believers.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 8, 1, 26, 12, 12, NULL, 'Fruitfulness and Blessing', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of yielding fruit and receiving a bountiful harvest. Mark speaks of varying yields, while Genesis highlights an abundant return of a hundredfold, showcasing God''s blessing on fruitful endeavors.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 8, 41, 4, 20, 20, 'good ground', 'Connection of Good Ground', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''good ground'' yielding fruit. They describe the process of receiving the word and producing varying amounts of fruit, reinforcing the idea of fruitful reception.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 8, 24, 23, 29, 29, 'yield fruit that sprang up', 'Fruitfulness of God''s Word', 'This connection highlights the productive nature of God''s word. Both passages emphasize the transformative power of God''s message, with Mark illustrating the fruitful yield and Jeremiah depicting the word''s ability to break barriers.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 8, 40, 13, 8, 8, 'good ground, and did yield fruit', 'Connection of Good Ground Fruit', 'Both passages emphasize the yield of fruit from good ground, highlighting the varying degrees of increase: some thirty, some sixty, and some a hundred. This connection illustrates a shared theme of productivity in fertile soil.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 8, 44, 17, 11, 11, 'yield fruit that sprang up', 'Nobility of Reception', 'This connection highlights the fruitful response to the word of God. Both passages emphasize the importance of readiness and growth in faith, as seen in the good ground yielding fruit and the noble Bereans searching the scriptures.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 9, 40, 11, 15, 15, 'He that hath ears to hear, let him hear.', 'Ears to Hear Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the phrase ''He that hath ears to hear, let him hear,'' highlighting the importance of listening and understanding. This repetition suggests a thematic link regarding the necessity of attentiveness to the message being conveyed.', 'keyword', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
